4. Why flask?
A: it is light weight and easy to deploy for devops projects. i used this because i dint have to build a complex application, i just had to focus on infrastructre,
   containerization, monintoring, deployment and scaling. I dint use Django framework because it is a full stack framework with many built in features like ORM and
   authentication. I just needed a simple application so i used flask.

5. Why Docker?
A: Docker packages the application with its dependencies into a container. This ensures that the application behaves consistently accross all dev, test, prod phases.
   thus eliminating "it only works only machine" issues. Its also portable, lightweight, easy deployment

6. Explain Docker Architecture
A: It has 3 main components: docker client, docker daemon, docker registry
   Docker client: users execute docker commands like docker build, docker run
   Docker Daemon : runs in backgroud, builds the images, containers, manages networking and storage
   Docker Registry: stores all the docker images. Ex: Docker hub, Amazon ECR

7. Diff btwn docker image and docker container
A: Docker image: Template, read only, static
   Docker container: Running instance, read and write, dynamic
      Once an image is created we can create many containers from one image. Ex: Image: Blueprint, Container: House

8. Explain your docker file
A: My docker file:
      FROM python:3.11
      WORKDIR /app
      COPY . .
      RUN pip install -r requirements.txt
      EXPOSE 5000
      CMD ["python","app.py"]
   1. From python means use the python3.11 image as base
   2. workdir/app means sets the working directory as /app inside the container
   3. Copy . . means copies the project files into the container
   4. Run pip line: installs python dependencies from requirements.txt file
   5. expose 5000: tells the application to listen to port 5000
   6. cmd : start the flask application when container launches

9. cmd vs entry point
A: cmd : default command, can be overriden easily
   entry point: fixed executable, always executed
      Ex: Example:
            CMD ["python","app.py"]
            can be overridden:
            docker run image bash
            ENTRYPOINT cannot be easily replaced without using --entrypoint.

10. copy vs add
A: copy: copies local files into the image
   add: can also extract local archives automatically and fetch files from url's
      use copy only, unless you specifically need to use add

11. Why expose port 5000?
A: Flask listens to port 5000, so when users open the website, nginx recieves the signal on port 80 and then forwards to flask on port 5000

12. Why dint u expose port 5000 directly?
A: Using nginx as a reverse proxy has many benefits: users dont enter port numbers, better security by hiding the aplication server, improved performance

13. Explain docker build
A: command: docker build -t app1 .
      this command reads the docker file, downloads the base image if needed, executes each command layer by layer, builds the image, names the image as app1 and . for
      current folder

14. Explain docker run
A: Command:docker run -d -p 5000:5000 app1
      creates a container from the app1 image, maps host port 5000 to container port 5000, -d for detach mode

15. Explain the commands
A: docker ps --> lists the current running containers
   docker ps -a --> lists all running, stopped containers 
   docker images --> gives list of all docker images stored locally
   docker logs <container> --> shows the application logs of that container
   docker exec -it <container> bash --> opens an interactive shell inside the container
   docker stop <container> --> stops the running container
   docker start <container> --> starts the stopped container
   docker restart <container> --> stops and starts the container
   docoker rm <container> --> removes the stopped container
   docker rmi <image> --> removes the docker image if no container depends on it

16. How to check logs?
A: Container logs : docker logs <container-id>
   nginx logs: tail -f /var/log/nginx/error.log
               tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log
   System services: journalctl -u nginx
                    journalctl -u docker

17. Diff between nginx restart and nginx reload
A: systemctl restart nginx --> stops and starts the nginx service, existing connections are interrupted
   systemctl reload nginx --> reloads the configuration without stopping the service, existing connections are not interrupted

18. Challenge in your project?
A: It was troubleshooting HTTP 502 and 503 errors.I systematically checked the Docker container status, verified the Flask application was listening on the 
   correct port, reviewed Nginx configuration and logs, validated security group rules, and confirmed the ALB health check path and port. I had to always run 
   the docker container again to solve this issue. By isolating each layer of the architecture, I identified the root cause and restored the application. 
   This experience improved my troubleshooting and production debugging skills




                  

